2.1.4 Helpful Features for Scripting
------------------------------------

GNU APL provides three system variables and functions that are
particularly useful for scripting:

   вАҐ вОХARG: access to the command line arguments given to the
     interpreter,
   вАҐ вОХENV: access to the environment variables of the process running
     the interpreter, and
   вАҐ вОХINP: Here-Document-alike function for creating large text
     variables

2.1.4.1 вОХARG
............

The system variable вОХARG contains all command line arguments passed to
the interpreter.  In the initial example above this would be a nested
3-element vector:

    /usr/local/bin/apl --id 1010

2.1.4.2 вОХENV
............

There are usually at least two ways of passing parameters to a script:

   вАҐ as command line options, and/or
   вАҐ by means of environment variables

   Just as the system variable вОХARG makes the command line options used
available to APL, so does the system function вОХENV make the environment
variables available to APL. Since there normally exist far more
environment variables than command line options, вОХENV is a monadic
function whose argument is a filter for the name(s) of the variable(s)
to be retrieved.

   вОХENV B returns all environment variables whose name starts with B. If
вНіB is 0, like:

    вОХENV ''

   then all environment variables of the process running GNU APL are
returned.

   The result of вОХENV is a (possibly empty) N√Ч2 matrix.  The first
column contains the name(s) of the environment variable(s), while the
second column contains their value(s).  The name and the value are both
strings.

   The number N of environment variables returned by вОХENV obviously
depends on the number of environment variables whose name begins with
the prefix given in B; shorter prefixes B therefore result in higher
counts N. B is case sensitive; by convention the names of environment
variables are all uppercase.  Note the subtle difference between shell
variables and environment variables in shells like bash: вОХENV returns
only environment variables (which are set with command setenv in bash),
but not shell variables (which are set with command set in bash).  For a
shell variable to occur in вОХENV it must be exported into the environment
of the process before the GNU APL interpreter is started.

2.1.4.3 вОХINP
............

If you need to create a longer static text, like the body of a web page,
then you would normally construct it in APL like this:

BODY вЖР вКВ 'First line'
BODY вЖР BODY , вКВ 'Second line'
BODY вЖР BODY , вКВ 'Third line'
   ...

   The above is obviously not very handy for longer texts.  Instead you
may write the following in a GNU APL script:

BODYвЖРвОХINP 'END-OF-вОХINP'
First line
Second line
Third line
   ...
END-OF-вОХINP

   This works like "Here documents" in bash.  The right argument of вОХINP
is the end of text marker.

   вОХINP also has a dyadic form where the left argument specifies an
escape sequence from text to APL and back to the text, similar to PHP
scripts.  For example:

ZвЖР'<?apl' '?>' вОХINP 'END-OF-вОХINP'
First line
Time is now: <?apl вНХвОХTS ?>
Third line
...
END-OF-вОХINP

   This creates a mainly static text with a small dynamic plug-in
computed by APL:

      вКГZ
First line                       
Time is now: 2022 8 4 15 15 2 177
Third line                       
...         

   It should be noted that, while вОХINP simplifies the construction of
multi-line strings compared to standard APL, it has come of age and
these days an even simpler feature - Multi-line strings as described
below - is provided for the same purpose.  The monadic вОХINP has
therefore become obsolete.


