вФГвФПвКЦвФУ вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФУ вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФБвФУ вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФУвФГ
вФГвФГ вФГ вФГABCвФГ вФГ DEFвФГ вФГ  GHIJKвФГвФГ
вФГвФЧвФБвФЫ вФЧвФБвФБвФБвФЫ вФЧвФБвФБвФБвФБвФЫ вФЧвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФЫвФГ
вФЧвИКвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФЫ

2.1.6.2 New-style Multi-Line Strings
....................................

The combination of вОХINP for immediate execution mode and multi-line
strings for defined functions achieved, at least in principle, the goal
of specifying large amounts of text in a simpler manner than in standard
APL. However, having different methods for creating multi-line string
literals in different APL modes could not convince entirely.

   The search for a more intuitive and more consistent solution then led
to new-style multi-line strings.  These strings adopted the triple quote
(""") syntax known from e.g.  the Python language.  The syntax of
new-style multi-line strings is cleaner: empty lines are handled more
consistently and the string lines are completely separated from the APL
code lines.  More importantly, new-style multi-line strings work alike
in immediate execution mode, in scripts, and in defined functions.
New-style strings are a little different and syntactically stricter than
their old-style companions:

   вАҐ the starting """ must be placed at the end of an APL code line,
     i.e.  there is no more mixing of APL code and string content on the
     same line.  An old-style string starts with APL code and ends with
     the first line of the string, while a new-style string starts with
     an APL code line and the string itself begins at the following
     line.

   вАҐ the ending """ must be placed at the end of a separate line with
     only spaces allowed before the """ (to horizontally indent-align it
     with the leading """ if so desired).  In old-style strings the text
     up to the termination " is part of the string while in new-style
     strings it is not.

   вАҐ Neither the starting nor the ending line become nested strings of
     the result, and every line can be clearly identified as being
     either APL code or else string text.

   Example:
 4 вОХCR """
ABC
 DEF

  GHIJK
       """
вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФУ
вФГвФПвЖТвФБвФБвФУ вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФБвФУ вФПвКЦвФУ вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФУвФГ
вФГвФГABCвФГ вФГ DEFвФГ вФГ вФГ вФГ  GHIJKвФГвФГ
вФГвФЧвФБвФБвФБвФЫ вФЧвФБвФБвФБвФБвФЫ вФЧвФБвФЫ вФЧвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФЫвФГ
вФЧвИКвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФБвФЫ

   When entering new-style multi-line strings, the prompt is prefixed by
вЖТ to indicate that a Multi-Line String is being entered.

   вОХINP and old-style strings will coexist for a while, but may
eventually disappear at some point in time.

2.1.6.3 ¬Ђ ¬ї Strings
...................

When new-style multi-line strings are used in scripts the related error
reporting (if the syntax is used incorrectly) can become cumbersome.
For example, if one forgets the closing """ of a multi-line string then
the next """ (which was meant as the start of a new multi-line string)
is mistaken as the (forgotten) end of the previous one.  The often long
content of the new string is then parsed as APL code and will usually
produce many error messages, all of them nonsense.  Things get worse if
the script itself is long because the odd/even nature of the quotes will
then persist until the end of the string (or at least until the next
forgotten quote, if any).

   To deal with this problem, GNU APL also allows strings whose contents
are enclosed in double angle quotation marks ¬Ђ and ¬ї.  In inline strings
вАЩ...вАЩ and "...", as well as in multi-line strings """ ...  """, there is
no general (and reliable) way to decide if a user has forgotten the
ending quote(s), which leads to the problems above.

   For this reason, GNU APL now also allows inline and multi-line
strings like, for example:

