2.17 Monadic вКҐ and вК£, dyadic вКҐ with Axis
========================================

Monadic вКҐ is the identity function.  It returns its (committed or
non-committed) right argument as a non-committed value.

   Conversely, monadic вК£ (called Hide in GNU APL) discards its
(committed or non-committed) right argument and returns a committed
integer scalar 0.

   For the most part there is no difference between a committed value (=
a value that was assigned to a variable, including вОХ and вНЮ) and a
non-committed value.  The point where it does make a difference is when
the value is the final result of a statement (as opposed to an
intermediate result inside a statement).  In that situation (and only
there) a non-committed value is printed but a committed value is not.

   You can use вКҐ in a similar fashion as вОХвЖР at the left end of a
statement, to print a value even though it was previously assigned to a
variable.

   The main motivation for вК£ is that, at least in GNU APL, lambdas
always return a value.  However, if a lambda is used only for the sake
of its side effects, say to print something, then the value returned by
the lambda is often of no interest and only messes up the APL output.
In that situation вК£ can be used to suppress the printing of undesired
return values from lambdas.

   In earlier GNU APL versions, вК£B and вКҐB would both return B; with вК£ as
committed value and with вКҐ as non-committed value.  But since the only
real-life purpose of вК£ is to suppress the printing of B, the
implementation of вК£ was changed to returning a committed integer scalar
0 instead of committed B. That reduced the run-time of вК£B from O(,B) to
O(1).  Also, вКҐB is marginally faster than вОХвЖРB.

   Dyadic вКҐ with axis is a selection function that generalizes вК£ and вКҐ.

   Let ZвЖРA вК£[X] B. Then:

   вАҐ if X is a one-element vector and вЖСX is 0 then Z вЙ° A,
   вАҐ if X is a one-element vector and вЖСX is 1 then Z вЙ° B,
   вАҐ otherwise X selects items of A or B if the corresponding elements
     of X are 0 or 1 respectively.  In that case, the shapes of A and B
     must match the shape of X, but one-element A or B are scalar
     extended to the shape of X.

   Example:

      AвЖР2 3вНі'abcdef'
      BвЖР2 3вНівН≥6
      XвЖР2 3вНі0 1 0 1 0 1
      A вКҐ[X] B
a 2 c
4 e 6

   A вКҐ[X] '*'
a*c
*e*

  '*' вКҐ[X] B
* 2 *
4 * 6


