2.18 Bit-wise Logical Functions вК§вИІ, вК§вИ®, вК§вН≤, вК§вН±, вК§вЙ†, and вК§=
==========================================================

The APL functions And (вИІ), Or (вИ®), Nand (вН≤), and Nor (вН±) operate
primarily on Boolean integers.  Primarily means that the LCM variant for
вИІ and the GCD variant for вИ® are not considered in this context.  (The
LCM and GCD variants are defined in the ISO standard and supported in
GNU APL but not in IBM APL2).

   However, probably more often than not one needs to compute Boolean
functions between the bits of arbitrary (non-Boolean) integers and not
between entire Boolean integers 0 or 1.  Although that is possible to do
in standard APL, the procedure is fairly awkward and, more importantly,
inefficient:

   вАҐ convert every integer argument X to a 64-item Boolean vector
     XвЖР(64вНі2)вК§X,
   вАҐ call the Boolean function вИІ, вИ®, вН≤, вН±, =, or вЙ† with the converted
     arguments, and
   вАҐ convert the Boolean result vector R back to the integer result
     ZвЖР2вК•R

   Note: for Boolean arguments the APL functions вЙ† and = can be used to
compute the more customary Boolean functions XOR and XNOR respectively.
In this context = and вЙ† are treated as Boolean functions even though
they accept non-Boolean arguments,

   For example, using 5 вОХCR (4вНі256)вК§X to display X in hex:

      5 вОХCR (4вНі256)вК§   AвЖР$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 вОХCR (4вНі256)вК§   BвЖР$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      5 вОХCR (4вНі256)вК§   2вК• ((64вНі2)вК§A) вИІ (64вНі2)вК§B
00BA00AD


   With the bit-wise And (вК§вИІ) the same can be achieved in a simpler
fashion and far more efficiently:

      вНЭ Traditional AND
      5 вОХCR (4вНі256)вК§   AвЖР$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 вОХCR (4вНі256)вК§   BвЖР$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      вНЭ bit-wise AND
      5 вОХCR (4вНі256)вК§   A вК§вИІ B
00BA00AD

2.18.1 Dyadic вК§вИІ, вК§вИ®, вК§вН≤, вК§вН±, вК§=, and вК§вЙ†
----------------------------------------

The dyadic forms of вК§вИІ, вК§вИ®, вК§вН≤, and вК§вН± are simply the bit-wise variants
of their Boolean counterparts:

      A вК§вИІ B    вЖРвЖТ    2вК• ((64вНі2)вК§A) вИІ (64вНі2)вК§B      вНЭ aka. AND
      A вК§вИ® B    вЖРвЖТ    2вК• ((64вНі2)вК§A) вИ® (64вНі2)вК§B      вНЭ aka. OR
      A вК§вН≤ B    вЖРвЖТ    2вК• ((64вНі2)вК§A) вН≤ (64вНі2)вК§B      вНЭ aka. NAND
      A вК§вН± B    вЖРвЖТ    2вК• ((64вНі2)вК§A) вН± (64вНі2)вК§B      вНЭ aka. NOR
      A вК§вЙ† B    вЖРвЖТ    2вК• ((64вНі2)вК§A) вЙ† (64вНі2)вК§B      вНЭ aka. XOR
      A вК§= B    вЖРвЖТ    2вК• ((64вНі2)вК§A) = (64вНі2)вК§B      вНЭ aka. NXOR or XNOR

2.18.2 Monadic вК§вИ® and вК§вН±
------------------------

вК§=, вК§вЙ†, and вК§вН≤ do not have a monadic form, but вК§вИІ, вК§вИ®, and вК§вН± do.
Formally monadic вК§вИ® and вК§вН± are dyadic вК§вИ® and вК§вН± with a left argument of
0:

      вК§вИ® B    вЖРвЖТ    0 вК§вИ® B      вНЭ real B to nearby integer
      вК§вН± B    вЖРвЖТ    0 вК§вН± B      вНЭ bit-wise Not

   Even though Or-ing a Boolean vector with 0 itself has no effect, the
monadic вК§вИ® and вК§вН± are still useful due to their side effects: conversion
from near-integer float values to integers (monadic вК§вИ® and inversion of
the bits (monadic вК§вН±, The latter is needed since вИЉ has a monadic form
and, as a consequence, вК§вИЉ was not an option for a bit-wise Not function.

   Monadic вК§вН± B is the bit-wise Not function of its argument:

   вК§вН± B вЖРвЖТ 2вК• ~(64вНі2)вК§B

   Monadic вК§вИ® B converts near-integer values B into true integers:

      26 вОХCR    1            вНЭ integer
16
      26 вОХCR    1.1          вНЭ real
32
      26 вОХCR    1√Ј1          вНЭ integer
16
      26 вОХCR    1.1√Ј1.1      вНЭ real
32
      26 вОХCR    вК§вИ® 1.1√Ј1.1   вНЭ integer
16

   That also works for complex numbers with a near-zero imaginary part:

      26 вОХCR    1.1J0√Ј1.1      вНЭ real
32
      26 вОХCR    вК§вИ® 1.1J0√Ј1.1      вНЭ integer
16

   As a matter of fact, вК§вИ® works for all near-Gaussian complex numbers,
but the effect is not visible with 26 вОХCR since Gaussian and
non-Gaussian complex numbers have the same cell type in GNU APL.

2.18.3 Monadic вК§вИІ
-----------------

The ISO standard defines two different concepts to decide if a real
number R is close to an integer I,
   вАҐ the real number R is said to be near to integer I if the absolute
     value of I-R is smaller than some small constant called the integer
     tolerance in ISO and system tolerance in IBM APL2.  The integer
     tolerance is typically platform dependent (1E¬ѓ10 in GNU APL).

   вАҐ the real number R is said to be equal to integer I within вОХCT if
     the absolute value of (I-R)/I is smaller than вОХCT.

   The first concept is an absolute distance from a real R to a nearby
integer I while the second concept is a relative distance (larger
numbers are allowed to be farther away from a nearby integer than
smaller numbers).  The two concepts differ in the same way that absolute
and relative errors do.

   Now, all bit-wise functions described so far use the first concept,
i,e, if their arguments are real or complex, then the smallest distance
to a (nearby) integer must not exceed the integer tolerance.  In some
contexts that could be difficult to achieve and for that reason GNU APL
provides monadic вК§вИІ which works like вК§вИ® except that the permitted
distance from a nearby integer is now controlled by вОХCT rather than by
the integer tolerance.

   All bit-wise logical functions throw a DOMAIN ERROR if an argument is
not close enough to an integer.  The integer tolerance is typically
smaller than вОХCT and in that case вК§вИІ is a little more tolerant than вК§вИ®
regarding the distance to nearby integers.  In addition вК§вИІ gives the
user (via вОХCT) more control over the permitted tolerance for real
numbers in the neighborhood of integers.

2.18.4 Character Arguments for Monadic вК§вН± and Dyadic вК§вИІ, вК§вИ®, ==, and вЙ†вЙ†
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

Some of the bit-wise operations are allowed to have characters as their
right argument.  If the right argument is a character then the result is
a character as well.  This can be useful for masking purposes such as
extracting the lower 7 bits of 8-bit bytes containing ASCII characters.

   The characters involved are treated as 32 bit quantities:

      5вОХCR 'A'
41
      5вОХCR вК§вН±'A'            вНЭ Note that 5вОХCR aka. вОХCR.to_HEX ANDs with $FF
BE

      256 256 256 256вК§ вОХUCS вК§вН± 'A'      вНЭ вК§вН± 'A' is FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190
      256 256 256 256вК§$FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190


