2.20 вМє[X] - QR and LQ Factorizations
====================================

2.20.1 вМє[1] and вМє[2] - QR Factorizations
----------------------------------------

ZвЖРвМє[1] B and ZвЖРвМє[2] B compute a QR factorization of the real or complex
matrix B. The results of ZвЖРвМє[1] B and ZвЖРвМє[2] B are conceptually
identical, while the algorithms used to compute the results differ.
Also, ZвЖРвМє[1] B always exist, while ZвЖРвМє[2] B requires libgsl to be
installed when GNU APL is compiled.

   The axis argument X is used to either clear near-0 matrix items to
exactly 0.0 during the computation (in Garry HelzerвАЩs algorithm), or
else to select a different algorithm for computing the factorization.
Set XвЖРвОХCT if unsure.

   The result Z is a triple (Q R Ri)вЖРZ with the following properties.
Let вНіB=(M, N).

   * Q is an orthogonal M√ЧM matrix, i.e Q^{-1} = Q^{T}, and Q +.√Ч вНЙQ is
the M√ЧM identity matrix I_{M} (with I_{M}вЖРвИШ.=вН®вН≥M).

   * R is an upper triangular N√ЧN matrix, i.e.  R[m;n] = 0 for all n <
m.  Note that if M>N then, following a convention in other libraries
(read: libgsl), the triangular matrices R and Ri have shape (N N) and
not (M N). This is because the rows below row N are always 0 in R and in
Ri, and are therefore not of interest.  As a consequence, in order to
