2.24 вОХDLX - KnuthвАЩs Dancing Links Algorithm
===========================================

вОХDLX is an implementation of Donald KnuthвАЩs Dancing Links Algorithm
(called DLX by Knuth himself, but is sometimes also referred to as
KnuthвАЩs Algorithm X). вОХDLX is a generic backtracking machine that can be
used to dramatically simplify problems like the 8 queens problem on a
chess board or sudokus.

   The monadic form of вОХDLX, i.e.  вОХDLX B, is a shortcut for 0 вОХDLX B.
It computes the first solution for the constraint matrix B.

   The dyadic form of вОХDLX, i.e.  A вОХDLX B, has an integer scalar A as
left argument which determines the details of the computation as
follows:

   A > 0: The algorithm tries to find all solutions, but stops when A
solutions have been found.  This is handy while debugging code using
вОХDLX. The result is a nested vector with one vector item per solution.

   A = 0: The algorithm stops when the first solution was found.  In
this case the solution is a simple (non-nested) numeric vector.

   A = ¬ѓ1: like A > 0 but finding all solutions

   A = ¬ѓ2: like A = 0 but instead of returning the first solution, the
number of solutions (i.e.  0 or 1), the number of backtracks, and the
number of link dances is returned as a 3-element numeric vector.

   A = ¬ѓ3: like A = ¬ѓ1 but instead of returning all solutions, the
number of solutions, the number of backtracks, and the number of link
dances is returned as a 3-element numeric vector.

   A = ¬ѓ4: A number of single steps in KnuthвАЩs Algorithm are performed.
Let e.g.  AвЖР¬ѓ4 r1 r2 r3.  Then ZвЖРA вОХDLX B is the matrix B after 3 steps
r1, r2, and r3 have been performed.  r1, r2, and r3 are valid (as per
вОХIO) row numbers of B, and a step with a given row changes B as follows:
   вАҐ the given row is set to 0 (this row becomes part of the final
     result),
   вАҐ all other rows that have a 1 or a 2 in the same column as B are set
     to 0 (these 1s or 2s in the other rows conflict with the 1 or 2 in
     the given row and are therefore removed from B), and
   вАҐ all columns that have no 1s or 2s left are removed from B (these
     columns have a 1 or 2 in B and the constraint is therefore
     satisfied).
   The purpose of ¬ѓ4 вОХDLX is:
   вАҐ To demonstrate how KnuthвАЩs algorithm works, and/or
   вАҐ To preset some initial values in B. For example, one can first
     initialize the constraints for an empty Sudoku (which is the same
     matrix for all Sudokus) and then enter the initial digits of a
     particular Sudoku using 4 вОХDLX. If there are, say, 20 initial
     digits in the Sudoku then A has 21 elements (¬ѓ4 plus the 20 rows
     representing the 20 initial digits.  The result of ¬ѓ4 вОХDLX B has
     the same number of rows as B (with some rows now cleared), but
     fewer columns than B.

   The right argument B of вОХDLX B or A вОХDLX B is a constraints matrix
whose columns consist of either 0s and 1s (called a primary column) or
0s and 2s (called secondary columns).  The 0s, 1s and 2s can be the
integers 0, 1, or 2, characters вАЩ0вАЩ, вАЩ1вАЩ, or вАЩ2вАЩ respectively, or вАЩ вАЩ
meaning вАЩ0вАЩ.  The character representation is useful when B becomes
large and shall be printed because the spaces in the numerical variant
will not be printed.  In the following, B is assumed to be numeric.

   Let ZвЖРA вОХDLX B, and let R be a solution in Z, that is, Z itself (A =
0) or R is Z[k] for some k if A вЙ† 0.  And let SвЖР+вМњB[R].

   Then S = s1 s2 s3, ...  sN where N is the number of columns in B and
sj=1 if j is a primary column of B and sjвИИ0 1 if j is a secondary column
of B.

   In other words, вОХDLX B computes a subset of the rows of B in such a
way that for every column j of B exactly one (for primary column j) or
at most one (for a secondary column) of the rows in a solution has its
jвАЩth element set to 1 and all other words set their jвАЩth element set to
0.

   In yet other words, for every solution returned by вОХDLX B, a 1 in one
row prevents all other rows that also have a 1 in that column, and all
rows together have exactly one 1 in every primary column and at most one
1 in every secondary column.  In the absence of secondary columns, the
problem solved by вОХDLX is also known as the "exact cover problem"

   If all that sounds weird and useless, consider the following APL
program for finding all solutions of the 8 Queens problem on a chess
board (which probably every programmer has programmed at some point in
time):

      RCвЖР8вЖС'1' вЧК DвЖР15вЖС¬ѓ8вЖС'2'   вНЭ helpers for constructing Q8
      вНЭ     rows   cols   diag1    diag2
      Q8вЖРвКГ{(RвМљRC),(CвМљRC),((C-R)вМљD),((¬ѓ7-R+C)вМљD)вК£(R C)вЖР-8 8вК§вНµ-вОХIO} ¬® вН≥64
      ZвЖР¬ѓ1 вОХDLX Q8
      {вОХUCS (65+вМКвНµ√Ј8)(49+8вИ£вНµвЖРвНµ-вОХIO)} ¬® вКГZ[1 2 3 92] вНЭ solutions 1, 2, 3, and 92
