   Obviously Z contains solutions for the 8 Queens problem; the total
number of solutions is well known to be 92 and we showed only the first
three and the last solution above.

   The constraint matrix Q8 is the key to success.  The matrix has 64
rows - one row for every field of the chess board.  And it has 8 + 8 +
15 + 15 columns.  The first 8 columns of Q8 are constraints that prevent
more than one Queen from being placed in the same row of the chess board
(the argument вНµ is the field number counting from left to right and from
bottom to top).  The next 8 columns of Q8 are constraints that prevent
more than one Queen from being placed in the same column of the chess
board.

   If we would call вОХDLX with only these constraints, i.e.  вОХDLX T8вЖР64
