2.31.12 Histograms
------------------

The histogram operation, вОХMX[12], is dyadic and requires a single
integer left argument (the number of buckets) and a real or complex
vector as a right argument (the samples).  It then creates an
equal-width-partition histogram of the samples contained in the
right-argument vector.  The width of each bucket is equal to the range
of the samples, max - min, divided by the number of buckets.  If the
samples are complex, the imaginary components are ignored.  As examples:

      4 вОХMX[12] (вН≥101)-вОХIO
25 25 25 26

   The distribution curves above were the result of expressions like:

      200 вОХMX[12] 200000 вОХMX[10 0] 1

   I.e.  a 200-bucket histogram of a 200 thousand-member vector of
normally distributed samples with a standard deviation of 1.

2.31.13 Print
-------------

The print operation, вОХMX[13], is dyadic and provides an easy way to dump
large quantities of data to files.  ItвАЩs left argument is a string
containing the file name to be created or, if the name starts with a
вАЬ>вАЭ, appended to.  The right argument may be a scalar, a vector, a
matrix, or a string.  For example:

      "samples.txt" вОХMX[13] 34
      ">samples.txt" вОХMX[13] 3 4
      ">samples.txt" вОХMX[13] 3 4вНівН≥12
      ">samples.txt" вОХMX[13] "example line"
      ">samples.txt" вОХMX[13] "example\nline"

