2.32 вОХPLOT - Plot Data
======================

вОХPLOT is a function for visualizing numerical APL values.  The values to
be plotted are provided as the right argument of вОХPLOT while the
optional left argument controls details of the output, such as the plot
window size, colors for plot lines, points, and grids, etc.

   The general syntax of вОХPLOT is:

   вОХPLOT вНђ       вНЭ show a list of attributes and their default values
   HвЖРвОХPLOT B     вНЭ plot B with all attributes set to their default values
   HвЖРA вОХPLOT B   вНЭ plot B with specified default attributes overridden
   вОХPLOT H       вНЭ close the plot window with handle H
   вОХPLOT  0      вНЭ verbosity: OFF (no debug output)
   вОХPLOT ¬ѓ1      вНЭ verbosity: ON (print attribute values before plotting)
   вОХPLOT ¬ѓ2      вНЭ verbosity: DEBUG (also print debug information)
   вОХPLOT ¬ѓ3      вНЭ close all plot windows
   вОХPLOT ¬ѓ6      вНЭ return all open plot window handles H

* Menu:

* Output File Format::

2.32.1 The Plot Data B
----------------------

The plot data B can be a vector (for a single plot line to be drawn) or
a matrix (in that case one plot line per matrix row is drawn, by default
in different colors).  Each data item has to be numeric and represents
one point in the plot.  The points that are adjacent in a row of the
matrix are connected by lines.  By default plotted points are black and
the lines connecting them are green (for the first plot line).  However,
all colors used, all diameters of points, and all thicknesses of the
lines can be fine-tuned by overriding the default values (see dyadic A
вОХPLOT B below).

2.32.1.1 Complex Plot Data B
............................

If a data item B[N] or B[row;N] is complex, say B[N] = x + iy.  then it
is placed (after some scaling) at position (x, y) of the plot.  The
X-range [Xmin ...  Xmax] of the plot is then determined by the real
parts of B, and the Y-range [Ymin ...  Ymax] of the plot is determined
by the imaginary parts of B. That is:

Xmin вЖР вМК/,9вЧЛB    вНЭ smallest real part of B
Xmax вЖР вМИ/,9вЧЛB    вНЭ largest real part of B
Ymin вЖР вМК/,11вЧЛB   вНЭ smallest imaginary part of B
Ymax вЖР вМИ/,11вЧЛB   вНЭ largest imaginary part of B

   Example (plot a circle (actually: a regular 20-gon)):

      вОХPLOT +вМњ1 0J1√Ч[1]1 2 вИШ.вЧЛ (0,вН≥2√ЧN) √Ч вЧЛ√ЈNвЖР10

   produces this plot window (only visible in the HTML version of this
document; in text mode see file doc/PLOT_circle.png):

␀[image src="PLOT_circle.png"␀]


2.32.1.2 Real Plot Data B
.........................

On the other hand, if a data item B[N] or B[row;N] is real, then it is
placed at position (N, x) of the plot.  The X-range is then [вОХIO ...
вОХIO + ¬ѓ1вЖСвНіB] and the Y-range [Y_{min} ...  Y_{max}] of the plot is
determined by the values of B. That is:

Xmin вЖР вОХIO             вНЭ smallest real part of B
Xmax вЖР ¬ѓ1 + вОХIO + вНіB   вНЭ largest real part of B
Ymin вЖР вМК/,B            вНЭ smallest value in B
Ymax вЖР вМИ/,B            вНЭ largest value in B

   Example:

      вОХPLOT 0 1 ¬ѓ1 2 ¬ѓ2 3 ¬ѓ3

   produces this plot window (only visible in the HTML version of this
document; in text mode see file doc/PLOT_zigzag.png):

␀[image src="PLOT_zigzag.png"␀]


   NOTE: In theory one can also mix real and complex values, even though
doing so makes little sense.  If at least one item of the plot data B is
complex, then all real items in B are taken as complex with imaginary
part 0.

2.32.2 The Plot Attributes A
----------------------------

There are a number of attributes like colors, point sizes, line widths,
etc.  that control how the resulting plot will look.

   Similar to вОХCR and вОХFIO, an empty argument B in вОХPLOT B displays a
list of the arguments.  The list of arguments grows over time and
therefore the list displayed by вОХPLOT вНђ may be more up-to-date than this
description.  For example:


   вОХPLOT Usage:

   вОХPLOT B     with вНівНіB > 0: plot B with default attribute values
   вОХPLOT B     with integer scalar B: special вОХPLOT functions
   A вОХPLOT B   plot B with attribute overrides specified by A

   A is a nested vector of strings.
   Each string A[i] has the form "Attribute: Value"
   Colors are specified either as #RGB or as #RRGGBB or as RR GG BB)

   The attributes understood by вОХPLOT and their default values are:

   1. Global (plot window) Attributes:

caption:            вОХPLOT          (plot window caption)
output_filename:                   (output file name)
auto_close:         0              (= do not close X window automatically)
                   (1)             (= close if file was written successfully)
                   (2)             (= always close X window automatically)
with_border:        1              (= write plot area and window borders)
                   (0)             (= write only plot area to output file)
pw_pos_X:           50 pixel       (plot window position X)
pw_pos_Y:           50 pixel       (plot window position Y)
border_width:       10 pixel       (width of the window border)
pa_width:           600 pixel      (plotarea width)
pa_height:          400 pixel      (plotarea height)
pa_border_L:        50 pixel       (pixels left of the plotarea)
pa_border_R:        20 pixel       (pixels right of the plotarea)
pa_border_T:        25 pixel       (pixels above the plotarea)
pa_border_B:        25 pixel       (pixels below the plotarea)
gridX_style:        1              (X grid style = вФАвФАвФАвФАвФАвФАвФАвФА )
                   (2)             (             = вХівХівХівХівХівХівХівХі )
                   (3)             (             = вФАвХівФАвХівФАвХівФАвХі )
axisX_arrow:        0              (X-axis arrow)
axisX_label:        X              (X-axis label)
axisY_arrow:        0              (Yaxis arrow)
axisY_label:        Y              (Y-axis label)
axisZ_arrow:        0              (Z-axis arrow)
axisZ_label:        Z              (Z-axis label)
gridX_pixels:       44 pixel       (pixels between X grid lines)
gridX_variable:     0              (draw X grid (only) at plot points)
gridX_line_width:   1 pixel        (thickness of the X-grid lines)
gridX_color:        #000000        (color of the X-grid lines)
gridY_style:        1              (Y grid style, see gridX_style above)
gridY_pixels:       33 pixel       (pixels between Y grid lines)
gridY_line_width:   1 pixel        (thickness of the Y-grid lines)
gridY_color:        #000000        (color of the Y-grid lines)
gridZ_style:        1              (Z grid style, see gridX_style above)
gridZ_pixels:       33 pixel       (pixels between Z grid lines)
gridZ_line_width:   1 pixel        (thickness of the Z-grid lines)
gridZ_color:        #000000        (color of the Z-grid lines)
canvas_color:       #FFFFFF        (background color of the plot window)
legend_color:       #F0F0F0        (background color of the legend)
legend_X:           50 pixel       (the X position of the legend)
legend_Y:           50 pixel       (the Y position of the legend)
legend_dY:          15 pixel       (the distance between legend lines)
legend_lX:          50 pixel       (the length of the legend lines)
rangeX_min:         0.0            (the start of the X range to be plotted)
rangeX_max:         0.0            (the end of the X range to be plotted)
rangeY_min:         0.0            (the start of the Y range to be plotted)
rangeY_max:         0.0            (the end of the Y range to be plotted)
rangeZ_min:         0.0            (the start of the Z range to be plotted)
rangeZ_max:         0.0            (the end of the Z range to be plotted)
origin_X:           100 pixel      (X position offset of the origin)
origin_Y:           100 pixel      (Y position offset of the origin)
format_X:           (none)         (format for X-axis ticks (GTK only))
                    %sT1%T2...%Tn  (static texts for ticks)
                    %G, %g         grid line number (starting at 1 or )
                    %v             value
                    %S             (seconds SS)
                    %I             (minutes MM)
                    %H, %h         (hours HH or h/hh)
                    %D, %d         (day DD or d/dd)
                    %M, %m         (month MM or m/mm)
                    %q             (quarter 0..3)
                    %Q             (quarter 1..4)
                    %Y, %y         (year YYYY or yy)
format_Y:                          (format for Y-axis (dito))
format_Z:                          (format for Z-axis (dito))

color_level-P:      (none)         (color gradient at P% (surface plots only))

   2. Local (plot line N) Attributes:

line_color-N:       #00FF00        (the color of plot line N)
line_style-N:       1              (line style, see gridX_style above)
line_width-N:       3 pixel        (the thickness of plot line N)
point_color-N:      #000000        (the color of the plot points)
point_style-N:      1              (= plot_points: вЧП )
                   (2)             (= plot_points: вЦ≤ )
                   (3)             (= plot_points: вЦЉ )
                   (4)             (= plot_points: вЧЖ )
                   (5)             (= plot_points: вЦ† )
                   (6)             (= plot_points: рЯЮ§   (GTK only)
                   (7)             (= plot_points: рЯЮЂ   (GTK only)
point_size-N:       8 pixel        (the outer diameter of the plot points)
point_size2-N:      0 pixel        (the inner diameter of the plot points)
legend_name-N:                     (the name of plot line N in the legend)


   There are 2 kinds of attributes: global attributes that affect the
entire plot, and local (per-line) attributes that affect one of the plot
lines (which corresponds to one row of B). One way to specify multiple
attributes in one go is to use multi-line strings.

   For example (plot 2 lines of 10 random numbers each, named "random
row 1" and "random row 2"):

      Data вЖР ?2 10вНі10   вНЭ two rows of random data
      Attributes  вЖР """
legend_name-1: Random Row 1
legend_name-2: Random Row 2
                    """
      Attributes вОХPLOT Data

   While specifying the plot attributes A in one place is most
convenient for a single plot window or when the attributes are read from
some external test file, it is sometimes simpler to specify the plot
attributes individually.  This can be done by using a structured APL
variable as left argument A:

Attributes.legend_name_1 вЖР "Random Row 1"
Attributes.legend_name_2 вЖР "Random Row 2"
      Attributes вОХPLOT Data

   Note that (for syntactical reasons) the separation between the line
attribute and the line number is _ (underscore) if A is specified as a
structured APL value and - (minus) if A is specified as a string of
lines.

   If the global attribute output_filename is given, then the plot is
not only displayed in a window on the screen, but also written to a file
with the name of the file provided as the value of the attribute.  *Note
Output File Format:: below.

   For example:

      вК£ ( вКВ "output_filename: /tmp/bitmap.png" ) вОХPLOT 1 3 1 4 2

   writes the plot of a a zigzag curve to file /tmp/bitmap.png.

   Caution: вОХPLOT with attribute output_filename overwrites existing
files without any warning).  Errors, most likely lack of permissions to
write the output file, raises a DOMAIN ERROR with )MORE possibly
providing details as to why the file could not be written.

   Some line attributes such as line_width or point_size are frequently
the same for several or even all plot lines.  In that case one can use
the line attribute without a -N or _N suffix which is then used as the
default for all lines (unless overridden by the same attribute with -N
or _N suffix.

   For example:

Attributes.line_width   вЖР 2   вНЭ all plot lines:     2 pixels thick,
Attributes.line_width_2 вЖР 4   вНЭ except plot line 2: 4 pixels thick

   As of GNU APL 1.9, вОХPLOT legends may be dragged to other locations
within a plot window using the usual click and drag GUI technique.

2.32.2.1 Tick formatting (GTK only)
...................................

By default, the ticks on the X, Y, and Z axes show the naked value of
their corresponding coordinates.  Sometimes you may want them to look a
little different, e.g.  by adding units to the numbers.  This can be
achieved with window properties format_X/Y/Z, possibly accompanied by
property gridX_variable.

   The properties format_X/Y/Z may be set to a format string that allows
the value that is being displayed at the ticks.  The format is a string
that is a mix of static text and tick items.  A tick item is computed
from the displayed value or from its position on the axis.  There are
two different types of tick items: static and dynamic.

   A static tick item starts with %s, followed by one or more texts,
separated by %.  The texts are displayed in the same order starting from
the origin and proceeding along the axis.  For example:

   ATT.format_X вЖР вАЩ%sT1%T2%T3вАЩ

   will name X-axis ticks T1, T2, and T3, regardless of the X
coordinate.  static tick items are the fallbacks for those cases where
dynamic tick items cannot produce the desired result.  In other words,
static tick items must be constructed in APL beforehand.

   In contrast, dynamic tick items are computed from the value at the
axis, which is often simpler than computing them beforehand in APL. A
format string may contain 0 or more tick items which are used in a
printf() like manner.

   Most of the dynamic tick items (see вОХPLOT вНђ for a complete list) are
related to points in time (years, quarters, months, days, hours,
minutes, and seconds).  For them the X coordinate (time) is, according
to the *nix time conventions, seconds since midnight 1970.  Since this
number of seconds is not easy to compute in APL, вОХFIO.secs_epoch comes
to rescue:

Q1  вЖР вОХFIO.secs_epoch 2023 2 15   вНЭ Feb. 15 (middle of Q1) 00:00:00

   An example for plotting the quarterly values 1 3 4 2 is:

      )CLEAR

SPQ вЖР 91√Ч24√Ч60√Ч60                 вНЭ seconds per quarter
Q1  вЖР вОХFIO.secs_epoch 2023 2 15   вНЭ Feb. 15 (middle of Q1) 00:00:00

X вЖР Q1 + SPQ√Ч0 1 2 3              вНЭ middles of Q1, Q2, Q3, and Q4
Y вЖР 1 3 2 4                       вНЭ values for Q1, Q2, Q3, and Q4

ATT.format_X вЖР "Q-%Q/%y"          вНЭ X-axis ticks: quarter and year

ATT вОХPLOT X + 0J1√ЧY


   Sometimes it is more convenient to display the exact X coordinates of
the plot points along the X axis instead of drawing an X-grid and
visually guessing the X-values between the vertical grid lines.  This
can be achieved with setting gridX_variable to 1.  Usually the
X-coordinates are evenly distributed along their axis while the Y and
Z-coordinates are not.  For this reason there is no gridY_variable or
gridZ_variable.

2.32.3 Plot Window Handling
---------------------------

Each call of вОХPLOT with some plot data B opens a separate window in the
X server (which implies that вОХPLOT requires X). That window runs in its
own thread until it is closed.  A plot window can be closed in different
ways:

   вАҐ interactively by clicking on the close button (often located near
     the top-right corner) of the plot window,
   вАҐ interactively by opening the drop down menu (if any) of the window
     (near the top left-of the window) and selecting the menu option
     named Close,
   вАҐ programmatically from APL by calling вОХPLOT ¬ѓ3 (which closes all
     open plot windows), or
   вАҐ programmatically from APL by calling вОХPLOT H (which closes a
     specific plot window), where H is the plot window handle returned
     by monadic вОХPLOT B, or by dyadic A вОХPLOT B with plot attributes A
     and plot data B.

   Note that the exact method for closing a plot window interactively
with the mouse or the keyboard (as opposed to programmatically with
вОХPLOT ¬ѓ3 or вОХPLOT H from APL) differs between different window managers.
The above corresponds to the typical method(s) for closing windows on
most systems.


