2.33 вОХPNG - Portable Network Graphics
=====================================

Portable Network Graphics is a file format for images, defined in *RFC
2083*.  To quote the RFC:

   вАШThe PNG format provides a portable, legally unencumbered,
well-compressed, well-specified standard for lossless bitmapped image
files.вАЩ

2.33.1 The GNU APL Color Model
------------------------------

An image is a rectangular matrix of *Pixels* which makes APL the perfect
language for manipulating images.  In GNU APL (and also in the PNG
standard) a single pixel may have one, two, three, or four color
components, or short colors, as follows:

   вАҐ a pixel with *one* color defines an uncolored (grayscale) pixel
     between black and white,
   вАҐ a pixel with *two* colors defines a grayscale pixel between black
     and white, and its opacity (see below),
   вАҐ a pixel with *three* colors defines a colored pixel whose colors
     are red, green and blue (or RGB for short), and
   вАҐ a pixel with *four* colors defines an RGB pixel and its opacity
     (RGBA for short).

   The opacity (sometimes called the "alpha channel" and abbreviated A
in the RGBA format) defines how transparent a pixel is; lower values
cause the background of a pixel to shine through while larger values
make the pixel more opaque.  One important use of the alpha channel is
images that shall not appear rectangular (even though their underlying
color matrix is).  For example, to display a red circle on top of
something else, one can set the opacity of the pixels inside the circle
to their maximum (as to making them fully opaque and completely hiding
the background or some other image below) and the pixels outside the
circle to 0 (making them fully transparent).

   Since every pixel of an image may have 1, 2, 3, or 4 color
components, the representation of an image in APL is a three dimensional
array *Image* where:

   вАҐ *(COLORS HEIGHT WIDTH) вЖР вНі IMAGE*,
   вАҐ *COLORS* is a number that determines *_general format_* of the
     image (and, by chance, the number of its color components):
        вАҐ *COLORS = 1*: a grayscale image,
        вАҐ *COLORS = 2*: a grayscale image with an alpha channel,
        вАҐ *COLORS = 3*: a colored RGB (red/green/blue) image, or
        вАҐ *COLORS = 4*: a colored RGB image with an alpha channel, aka.
          RGBA)
   вАҐ *Height* is the number of pixels of the image in the vertical
     direction, and
   вАҐ *Width* is the number of pixels of the image in the horizontal
     direction.

   Above is: *WIDTH* the number of pixels in the horizontal direction,
*HEIGHT* the number of the pixels in the vertical direction, and
*COLORS* the number of color components as above.  For simplicity we can
treat the opacity as yet another color although, strictly speaking, it
is not.

   For an image I, the horizontal pixel position I[;;x] increases from
left to right and the vertical pixel position I[;y;] increases from top
to bottom.

   In addition to the 4 general image formats above, the PNG standard
allows each format to have different resolutions (of 1-bit, 2-bit,
4-bit, 8-bit, and 16-bit, even though not all combinations of image
format and resolution are permitted.  For example, the lower resolutions
(of 1-bit, 2-bit, or 4-bit) are only permitted for grayscale images
without alpha channel, 16-bit is allowed for all images except those
with a color table, and so on.

   In theory there are 20 different combinations of 4 general image
formats and 5 resolutions of the color components.  However, the PNG
standard allows only 15 of them, in particular by permitting 1-bit,
2-bit, 4-bit resolutions only for grayscale images without alpha
channel.  The GNU APL color model reduces these 15 combinations further
to the 4 general types with the following rules:

   вАҐ On input, i.e.  when reading a PNG image file and producing the APL
     array described above, the different resolutions allowed by the PNG
     standard are normalized to a single range of real numbers between
     0.0 and 1.0 (this is by chance also the range used in the GTK
     standard used in вОХPNG and вОХPLOT).
   вАҐ Also on input, images that use color tables (for compressing the
     image to reduce the file size) are automatically expanded.  The
     resulting APL value is therefore independent of the use of color
     tables.
   вАҐ On output, i.e.  when storing the APL array in a PNG file, the
     resolution is 8-bit by default.  8-bit is the only resolution which
     is valid for all image formats in the PNG standard.
   вАҐ Also on output, one may optionally specify a different resolution.

   In GNU APL, integers and floating point numbers take the same space
in memory.  The advantage of smaller PNG files with lower resolutions
would therefore disappear as soon as converted to APL. On the other
hand, the disadvantage (primarily different max.  values for different
resolutions) would remain.  In the GNU APL color model a purely red RGB
pixel has the same value *I[;y[x] вЖР 1.0 0.0 0.0* regardless of
resolution, which simplifies matters considerably.  In a PNG file that
same red RGB pixel would instead have either:

   вАҐ the value $01 0 0 in a 1-bit RGB image, or
   вАҐ the value $03 0 0 in a 2-bit RGB image, or
   вАҐ the value $07 0 0 in a 4-bit RGB image, or
   вАҐ the value $FF 0 0 in a 8-bit RGB image, or
   вАҐ the value $FFFF 0 0 in a 16-bit RGB image.

   It may be useful to note that the human eye can only distinguish
around 120 different colors, i.e.  about 7 bits (for all color planes
together).  For this reason 16-bit color components are quite an
overkill and the 8-bit default therefore should be more than sufficient
for most purposes.

2.33.2 Monadic вОХPNG
-------------------

Monadic вОХPNG, i.e.  вОХPNG B is used for 3 purposes:

  1. Conversion of PNG files into the GNU APL color model,
  2. Display of an APL array (in the GNU APL color model) in a window on
     the screen (interactive use of PNG), and
  3. Controlling of вОХPNG itself.

   The desired purpose is dictated by the properties of *B*:

  1. Any APL text vector (i.e.  a string) *B* is taken as the name of a
     file that supposedly contains an image in the PNG format.  вОХPNG
     will read the file and return the pixels in it as a numeric APL
     array of rank 3.  The array contains the color components of the
     image in the file as described above.
  2. Any array *B* with rank 3 must be numeric (with values from 0.0 to
     1.0) and is then assumed to be an array in the GNU APL color model
     (such as the result of the case above).  This image is displayed in
     a new window on the screen; the window survives even after вОХPNG has
     returned.  The result returned by вОХPNG is a window handle (a
     positive integer identifying the window) which may later be used
     (in the case described below) to close the window programmatically
     from APL. Alternatively the window can also be closed interactively
     by the user via its close button.
  3. Finally, if *B* is a numeric scalar it fine-tunes the вОХPNG
     behaviour:

        вАҐ вОХPNG N with N вЙ• 1 (as returned in the case above) closes the
          window with handle N programmatically.

        вАҐ вОХPNG 0 disables all debug printouts related to вОХPNG.
        вАҐ вОХPNG ¬ѓ1 turns on a debug printout related to вОХPNG (X events).
        вАҐ вОХPNG ¬ѓ2 turns on a debug printout related to вОХPNG (image
          data).
        вАҐ вОХPNG ¬ѓ3 closes all open вОХPNG windows.
        вАҐ вОХPNG ¬ѓ4 turns on a debug printout related to вОХPNG (GTK
          drawing).
        вАҐ вОХPNG ¬ѓ5 turns on a debug printout related to вОХPNG (function
          calls).
        вАҐ вОХPNG ¬ѓ6 returns a vector of all open вОХPNG window handles.

2.33.3 Dyadic вОХPNG
------------------

Dyadic *A вОХPNG B* has only one purpose: to store an APL array in the GNU
APL color model into a PNG file.

   вАҐ If *A* is a text vector then it is taken as the name of a PNG file
     into which the image *B* shall be written.  In this case the
     resolution is 8 bits for each color component.
   вАҐ If *A* is a 2-element vector, say *(A1 A2) вЖР A*, then the nested
     *A1* is the name of a PNG file as before and *A2* is the resolution
     (1, 2, 4, 8, or 16) to be used for the output file.  In this case
     the combination of the general image format (as implied by *вЖСвНіB*)
     and resolution *A2* must be a valid one in the PNG standard.

2.33.4 APL Examples
-------------------

      вНЭ load PNG file image.png
      Image вЖР вОХPNG 'image.png'

      вНЭ display the image
      Handle вЖР вОХPNG Image

      вНЭ close the window that displays the image
      вОХPNG Handle

      вНЭ display PNG file image.png without storing it in a variable
      вОХPNG вОХPNG 'image.png'

      вНЭ Simple color conversions...

      вНЭ convert a monochrome image into the equivalent RGB image
      RGB_Gray вЖР 3 вМњ Mono

      вНЭ paint all pixels of a monochrome image red
      RGB_Red вЖР 1 0 0 вНА Mono

      вНЭ paint all pixels of a monochrome image green
      RGB_Green вЖР 0 1 0 вНА Mono

      вНЭ paint all pixels of a monochrome image blue
      RGB_Blue вЖР 0 0 1 вНА Mono


