2.35 вОХRE - Regular Expressions
==============================

вОХRE is a function that provides access to a subset of libpcre2, which is
a powerful regular expression matching library.  "pcre" is an acronym
for "Perl compatible regular expressions".  libpcre2 is Copyright (c)
1997-2017 University of Cambridge, England.

2.35.1 Preconditions
--------------------

libpcre2 is NOT shipped with GNU APL but must be installed before the
GNU APL ./configure script is executed.  The ./configure script tries to
locate libpcre2 and enables вОХRE if the library (and its header files)
are found.

   If ./configure does not find libpcre2, then вОХRE will raise a SYNTAX
ERROR when вОХRE is used in an APL program.

2.35.2 Syntax
-------------

вОХRE has two forms.  The short form (without an axis argument) is
intended to cover the most likely use cases of вОХRE, while the long form
gives more control over the format of the result produced by вОХRE:

Z вЖР A вОХRE B      (short form, no axis)
Z вЖР A вОХRE[X] B   (long form, with axis X)

   The short form is equivalent to the long form with an empty axis:

    A вОХRE B   вЖРвЖТ   A вОХRE[''] B

   It therefore suffices to explain the long form.  The long form has 3
different arguments A, B, and X.

2.35.3 The Regular Expression A
-------------------------------

A is a simple character vector which is expected to be a regular
expression as defined for the libpcre2 library.  вОХRE passes its left
argument A unmodified to libpcre2.  The format of A ranges from very
simple REs to very complex REs.  In fact, regular expressions are a
language of their own, and it is unnecessary to describe them here.  The
user of вОХRE is referred to the description that comes with libpcre2.

   See in particular: man pcre2pattern

2.35.4 The String(s) B Being Matched
------------------------------------

B is either:

  1. a simple character vector (which is then also passed unmodified to
     libpcre2), or

  2. a (nested) APL array consisting of simple character vectors.

   In the second case above, the result of вОХRE is conceptually the same
as if the EACH operator had been applied to вОХRE:

    A вОХRE B   вЖРвЖТ   A вОХRE ¬® B

   The libpcre2 first compiles A into an internal representation that
improves the speed of matching B. As a consequence, if several strings
shall be matched with the same regular expression A, then it is
(sometimes considerably) faster to A вОХRE B once with several items of a
nested B, than to A вОХRE B multiple times with the same A but different
Bs.  This is especially true when longer text files with many lines will
be matched.

   If multiple (nested) strings B are used then A is compiled once and
after that the different вКГB[i] in B are passed unmodified to libpcre2.
In that case the result Z is nested and (вНіB) вЙ° (вНіZвЖРA вОХRE[X] B). We can
therefore limit the description to the case where B is a simple
character vector.

   Any string B that is passed to libpcre2 is called "Subject" in the
libpcre2 documentation.

2.35.5 The Flags X
------------------

By default, i.e.  without an axis argument X or - equivalently - with an
empty string XвЖР"" as axis argument, вОХRE returns the first match of the
regular expression A in the string B as an APL string.

   By means of the optional axis argument X вЙҐ "" (called flags below)
one may override the default behavior to adapt various aspects of the
matching to satisfy the requirements that the user of вОХRE may have.

   The X argument of AвОХRE[X] B is a character vector where each
character is a flag.  Each flag is either understood by (and then passed
unmodified to) libpcre2 or else understood by вОХRE itself (and then not
passed to libpcre2).

2.35.5.1 The libpcre2 flags: i, m, s, and x
...........................................

The libpcre2 flags accepted by вОХRE are: i, m, s, and x.  They correspond
to the following libpcre2 flags:

   вАҐ i: PCRE2_CASELESS (perform case insensitive matching)
   вАҐ m: PCRE2_MULTILINE (perform matching across multiple lines)
   вАҐ s: PCRE2_DOTALL (dot (.)  in A also matches CR/LF)
   вАҐ x: PCRE2_EXTENDED (see вАЩman pcre2patternвАЩ)

   Please consult the libpcre2 documentation for a more detailed
description of these flags.

2.35.5.2 The вОХRE (APL output format) flags вЖУ, вКВ, and /
......................................................

вОХRE provides different output formats, some of which are tailored to
different APL functions, so that these other APL functions can use the
result of вОХRE without major conversions.  There are currently 4
different output formats:

   вАҐ no вОХRE flag: вОХRE returns the matching sub-string(s) of B.

   вАҐ вЖУ flag: вОХRE returns the position(s) and the length(s) of the
     matched sub-string of B, Like other left arguments of вЖС or вЖУ, the
     string position(s) in the result start at 0 (i.e.  not at вОХIO) and
     can therefore be used directly by dyadic вЖУ and вЖС.  For instance to
     cut out the matched pieces.

   вАҐ вКВ flag: вОХRE returns an integer vector suitable as the left argument
     of partition (dyadic вКВ).

   вАҐ / flag: вОХRE returns a Boolean vector suitable as the left argument
     of compress (dyadic /).

   The following examples may better explain the nature of the output
flags:

      вНЭ return (first) matched string
      4 вОХCR 'f..' вОХRE[''] '__foo___fun____fox'
вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФУ
вФГfooвФГ
вФЧвФБвФБвФБвФЫ

      вНЭ return (first) pair (position, length)
      4 вОХCR 'f..' вОХRE['вЖУ'] '__foo___fun____fox'
вФПвЖТвФБвФБвФУ
вФГ2 3вФГ
вФЧвФБвФБвФБвФЫ

      вНЭ return left argument A of A вКВ B
