2.36 вОХRVAL - Random APL value
=============================

The standard way to produce random numbers is the primitive function ?
aka.  Roll.  Roll returns a simple random array whose ravel elements are
positive integers chosen in a (pseudo-) random fashion.  While this is
sufficient for many applications, one sometimes needs APL values whose
randomness not only affects the ravel elements themselves, but also
other aspects like:

   вАҐ the rank of the value,
   вАҐ the shape of the value,
   вАҐ the data type of the ravel elements, and
   вАҐ the depth (nesting) of the values.

   Such values can be produced with system function вОХRVAL. The main use
case for вОХRVAL is the production of test data for the interpreter, but
вОХRVAL might be useful for other purposes as well.

2.36.1 General
--------------

In general, monadic вОХRVAL B, returns a single random APL value Z, while
dyadic A RVAL B is used to control the properties of subsequently
generated random APL values returned by monadic вОХRVAL.

   The typical use of вОХRVAL is to first call A вОХRVAL B zero or more
times to override individual default properties of the subsequently
produced values, followed by one or more calls of monadic вОХRVAL B.

   The default properties, i.e.  the properties used unless they were
overridden by dyadic A вОХRVAL B, are:

Rank:  0
Shape: 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 (initially irrelevant since Rank = 0)
Type:  0 1 0 0 0       (only integer random values)
Max. Depth: 4          (initially irrelevant since type = 0 1 0 0 0)

   With these default properties, every call of monadic вОХRVAL B returns
an integer scalar.

2.36.2 Dyadic вОХRVAL
-------------------

The left argument A of A вОХRVAL B determines which aspect of the
subsequent random APL values shall be controlled.  A is an integer
scalar:

   вАҐ A=0 controls the state of the underlying random number generator,

   вАҐ A=1 controls the ranks of the subsequent random APL values,

   вАҐ A=2 controls the shapes of the subsequent random APL values,

   вАҐ A=3 controls the data types in the ravels of the subsequent random
     APL values, and

   вАҐ A=4 controls a maximum depth of the subsequent random APL values.

2.36.2.1 Control of the underlying random number generator: 0 вОХRVAL B
.....................................................................

вОХRVAL uses the standard C function random_r().  For this reason вОХRVAL is
only available on platforms which use glibc, for example all GNU/Linux
systems.

   Every random number generator has a state (similar to вОХRL for вАЩ?вАЩ).
While the primitive ?  keeps its state in вОХRL, i.e.  in the workspace,
вОХRVAL has no associated system variable like вОХRL which keeps its state.
Instead, the user needs to store the state of вОХRVAL in a workspace
variable if the workspace shall be stored and continued at a later
point.  This rarely happens, therefore no effort was spent on
implementing another system variable.  For the same reason, the state of
вОХRVAL survives )CLEAR.

   The current state of вОХRVALвАЩs random number generator can be retrieved
with:

      STATE вЖР 0 вОХRVAL ''

   The state changes with every call of monadic вОХRVAL. The random number
generator can later be restored to the same state like this:

      0 вОХRVAL STATE

   Restoring the state is needed when the same sequence of random values
shall be generated again.  The random number generators of ?  and вОХRVAL
are independent; generating a random number or random value with one
does not change the state of the other.

2.36.2.2 Control of the ranks: 1 вОХRVAL B
........................................

The rank of subsequently generated random values can be controlled with
1 вОХRVAL B as follows:

   вАҐ If B is a non-negative scalar with 0 вЙ§ B < MAX_RANK then the
     subsequently generated random values will have the fixed rank B.
     MAX_RANK is a ./configurable constant with a default of 8.

   вАҐ If B is a negative scalar with 0 > B > -MAX_RANK then the ranks of
     the subsequently generated random values will be chosen at random
     between 0 and -B (inclusive).  All possible ranks 0 ...  B will
     have the same probability P = 100√Ј1-B %.

   вАҐ Otherwise B must be a vector of positive integers.  The integers
     are the relative frequencies of the ranks 0, 1, ...  MAX_RANK
     respectively.  Too many integers (i.e.  MAX_RANK > вНіB) will raise a
     LENGTH ERROR while fewer (than MAX_RANK) are set to 0.

   1 вОХRVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  1 вОХRVAL вНђ will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 1 вОХRVAL.

   Examples:

   вАҐ 1 вОХRVAL 2 will produce only matrices,

   вАҐ 1 вОХRVAL ¬ѓ2 will produce scalars, vectors or matrices, each with a
     probability of 100√Ј3 %, and

   вАҐ 1 вОХRVAL 50 30 20 will produce scalars with probability 50%, vectors
     with probability 30%, and matrices with probability 20%.  The
     numbers need not add up to 100, but will be scaled accordingly.

2.36.2.3 Control of the shapes: 2 вОХRVAL B
.........................................

The shapes of subsequently generated random values can be controlled
with 2 вОХRVAL B as follows.

   B must be a vector of positive or negative integers.  Vectors longer
than MAX_RANK + 1 will give a LENGTH ERROR while vectors shorter than
MAX_RANK + 1 will be filled with 1 until the length of B becomes
MAX_RANK + 1.

   If an element B_{i} of the resulting shape B = B_{1} ...  B_{MAXRANK}
is вЙ• 0 then the corresponding axis i will have a fixed length of B_{i}.
If B_{i} < 0 then the length of that axis will be chosen at random with
a probability of 1√ЈB_{i}.  Note that the same B can still produce
different shapes even if all B_{i} are вЙ• 0 (i.e.  if the rank is also
chosen at random).

   2 вОХRVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  2 вОХRVAL вНђ, will not change anything and can be
used to query the current setting for 2 вОХRVAL.

   Example:

1 вОХRVAL 2        вНЭ produce matrices
2 вОХRVAL 3 ¬ѓ10    вНЭ the first axis of every matrix will have length 3, and
                 вНЭ the last axis of every matrix will vary between 0 and 10

   This will produce scalars, vectors with a fixed length of 3 and
matrices with 3 rows and between 0 and 10 columns.

2.36.2.4 Control of the data types: 3 вОХRVAL B
.............................................

The types (i.e.  CHARACTER, INTEGER, REAL, COMPLEX, or NESTED) of
subsequently generated random values can be controlled with 3 вОХRVAL B as
follows.

   B must be a vector with up to 5 positive numbers, corresponding to
the types.  Shorter vectors are filled with 0 (the corresponding types
will not occur) and longer vectors will raise a LENGTH error.

   Once the type was chosen, the ravel item will be:

   вАҐ for type CHARACTER: a random character with вОХUCS between 0 and
     $3000 (exclusive).  Larger Unicodes typically cause display
     problems.  If you need larger Unicodes, use вОХUCS with random
     integers.

   вАҐ for type INTEGER: a random integer with вОХUCS between -$80000000 and
     $7FFFFFFF.

   вАҐ for type REAL: a floating point number between 0.0 and 1.0
     (exclusive)

   вАҐ for type COMPLEX: a complex point number with real and imaginaty
     part between 0.0 and 1.0 (exclusive), and

   вАҐ for type NESTED: a nested APL value with the same properties (rank,
     shape, and type) as their parent.

   3 вОХRVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  3 вОХRVAL вНђ will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 3 вОХRVAL.

   Example:

      1 вОХRVAL 2         вНЭ produce matrices
      2 вОХRVAL 3 3       вНЭ produce 3√Ч3 matrices
      3 вОХRVAL 0 50 50   вНЭ produce a mix of integer and real values
      вОХRVAL ''
¬ѓ975954163190248487                   0.5892132425
7677327503669503253 2152001972871424768

2.36.2.5 Control of a maximum depth: 4 вОХRVAL B
..............................................

If the probability of generating a nested value is > 0 then the depth of
random values can become arbitrarily large and could therefore exceed
the system limit for the depth of the random value being produced.  This
can be prevented by setting a maximum depth for every value generated.
вОХRVAL sets the probability of the deepest allowed depth to 0.

   4 вОХRVAL B expects B to be a positive integer which is deepest allowed
depth;

   An empty B, e.g.  4 вОХRVAL вНђ, will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 4 вОХRVAL.

2.36.2.6 monadic вОХRVAL B: Return a new random value
...................................................

Calling вОХRVAL monadically produces one new random APL value.

   The properties of that next value can be controlled by the dyadic
calls of вОХRVAL as described above.  If no prior dyadic call of вОХRVAL was
made then the properties have the following defaults:

      1 вОХRVAL вНђ    вНЭ rank (scalar)
0

      2 вОХRVAL вНђ    вНЭ shape (not used since rank = 0)
1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1

      3 вОХRVAL вНђ    вНЭ types (integer)
0 1 0 0 0

      4 вОХRVAL вНђ    вНЭ max. depth (not used since probability of NESTED = 0)
4

   That is, by default, вОХRVAL вНђ produces random integer scalars.

   It is sometimes convenient to be able to change the properties of the
next random value without modifying (and later restoring) the properties
with dyadic вОХRVAL. This can be achieved with monadic вОХRVAL with
non-empty B.

   Let 4=вНіB. Then

   ZвЖРвОХRVAL B does essentially:

   B[1]вЖР1 вОХRVAL B[1]
   B[2]вЖР2 вОХRVAL B[2]
   B[3]вЖР3 вОХRVAL B[3]
   B[4]вЖР4 вОХRVAL B[4]

   ZвЖРвОХRVAL ''

   B[1]вЖР1 вОХRVAL B[1]
   B[2]вЖР2 вОХRVAL B[2]
   B[3]вЖР3 вОХRVAL B[3]
   B[4]вЖР4 вОХRVAL B[4]

   If 4 > вНіB then the missing properties are not changed.

   Examples:

вОХRVAL 1 (,¬ѓ4) (0 1)    вНЭ return a random 0-4 element integer vector
вОХRVAL 2 (2 2) (1 0)    вНЭ return a random 2√Ч2 character array


2.36.2.7 Syntax Alternatives
............................

For an improved readability, вОХRVAL also accepts string arguments for its
left argument A and also the subfunction notation:

      0 вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  'state' вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  вОХRVAL.state B
      1 вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ   'rank' вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  вОХRVAL.rank  B
      2 вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  'shape' вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  вОХRVAL.shape B
      3 вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ   'type' вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  вОХRVAL.type  B
      4 вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  'depth' вОХRVAL B  вЖРвЖТ  вОХRVAL.depth B


