2.38 вОХSI - State Indicator
==========================

вОХSI returns aspects of the current State Indicator, similar to the
standard command )SI. This can be used, for example, to create debug
functions similar to the assert() macro in C/C++:


вИЗAssert B;COND;LOC;VAR
 вЖТ(1вЙ°B)вНі0
 ' '
 CONDвЖР7вЖУ,¬ѓ2 вОХSI 4
 LOCвЖР,¬ѓ2 вОХSI 3
 '************************************************'
 ' '
 '*** Assertion (', COND, ') failed at ',LOC
 ''

 вНЭ show stack
 вНЭ
 ' '
 'Stack:'
 7 вОХCR вКГ¬ѓ1вЖУвОХSI 3
 ' '
 '************************************************</pre>'
 вЖТ
вИЗ


   The right argument of вОХSI specifies which aspect of the State
Indicator shall be returned:

   вАҐ вОХSI 1: The name of the context.  That name is either:
        вАҐ the name of a defined function, or
        вАҐ вЧК for an immediate execution context, or
        вАҐ вНО for an execute context.

   вАҐ вОХSI 2: The line number (of a defined function) or 0 for immediate
     execution and execute contexts.

   вАҐ вОХSI 3: The function name and line number in square brackets, for
     example: "FOO[3]"

   вАҐ вОХSI 4: Either the statement text of the function line or the error
     text of an error that has occurred on the line

   вАҐ вОХSI 5: The program counter (= token number counted from the start
     of the function text)

   вАҐ вОХSI 6: the parse mode of the context (immediate execution, execute,
     or defined function).

   If no left argument is provided then the result of вОХSI is a vector
with one entry per State Indicator level (and hence вНівОХSI B is the depth
of the SI stack).

   If the optional left argument A is provided then it specifies a
particular level of the SI instead of the entire SI. A should be an
integer scalar.  If A is positive then the level is counted from the
oldest entry to the latest, while negative A counts from the latest to
the oldest level.

   For example, ¬ѓ1 вОХSI refers to the currently executing context, ¬ѓ2 вОХSI
is the caller, and so on.


