2.40 вОХXML - XML Parsing
=======================

2.40.1 Purpose
--------------

GNU APL provides вОХXML as a means of performing elementary manipulations
of APL character strings that are formatted according to the XML
standard.  The anticipated procedure for such modifications is something
like:

      XML_string вЖР "<A><B><C>Hello</C></B></A>"   вНЭ input data (usually from an .xml file)
      APL вЖР вОХXML XML_string       вНЭ convert XML_string to associative array APL
      ABC вЖР APL.a.b.c             вНЭ retrieve node a.b.c in APL
      APL.a.b.c вЖР ABC, " World"   вНЭ modify node a.b.c in APL
      Z вЖР вОХXML APL                вНЭ convert associative array APL to XML string Z

      ABC   вНЭ the original value of XML.a.b.c
Hello
      Z     вНЭ the modified XML string
<A><B><C>Hello World</C></B></A>"

   The scope (functionality) of вОХXML is then:

   вАҐ Conversion of (valid) XML strings to associative APL arrays that
     can be more easily processed in APL than the XML strings,
   вАҐ Conversion of associative APL arrays back to valid XML strings,
   вАҐ Simple (at APL level) access to the data contained in XML strings,
     and
   вАҐ Transparent access to those (mostly XML specific) portions of the
     XML string that are not (yet) handled by вОХXML; this means that the
     user of вОХXML shall be able to handle advanced XML aspects (like
     document type declarations (DTDs), document validation, etc.)  in
     APL without much overhead.

2.40.2 Some XML Terminology
---------------------------

An XML document is a character string with a standardized format.  The
characters must be valid XML characters as defined in the XML standard
(almost all Unicode characters except most of the ASCII control
characters).  GNU APL raises a DOMAIN ERROR when an XML document
contains invalid XML characters.

   The XML document is a sequence of adjacent sub-strings, where each
sub-string is:

   вАҐ either markup (-string),
   вАҐ or non-markup (-string).

   A markup (sub-)string:

   вАҐ starts with character вАЩ<вАЩ, and
   вАҐ ends with character вАЩ>вАЩ, and
   вАҐ all other characters in the markup string differ from вАЩ<вАЩ and вАЩ>вАЩ.

   A non-markup (sub-)string:

   вАҐ starts either at the beginning of the XML document or else directly
     after a markup string,
   вАҐ end at the end of the document or else directly before a markup
     string, and therefore
   вАҐ cannot be adjacent to another non-markup string.

   Non-markup is sometimes referred to as "unstructured text".  The
producer of an XML document has a principal choice about where to locate
the information that the document contains: in the unstructured text or
in the attribute values inside the tags.  For that reason the XML
standard is somewhat picky about keeping the unstructured text as well
as attribute values intact and requires that whitespace in non-markup
(the only allowed whitespace characters in XML being TAB, CR, LF, and
SPACE) is preserved in non-markup strings.

   As a consequence, many non-markup strings begin with LF because the
preceeding markup was on the previous line and therefore the LF after
the preceeding markup is whitespace of the non-markup and therefore
needs to be preserved.

   Every markup belongs to one of 4 categories:

   вАҐ Processing instructions: "<?  ...  ?>",
   вАҐ Comments: "<!вАФ ...  вАФ>",
   вАҐ Declarations "<!  ...  !>", and
   вАҐ Tags, which are either:
        вАҐ Empty tags (leaf tags): "<tagname attributes...  />
        вАҐ Start tags: "<tagname attributes...  >, or
        вАҐ End tags: "</tagname>

   The XML tags recursively define a tree structure where:

   вАҐ the nodes of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
     followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup, comments,
     and sub-nodes (of the tree), followed by an end tag (with the same
     name as the start tag),
   вАҐ the leafs of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
     followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup and comments,
     followed by an end tag (with the same name as the start tag).  The
     difference between a leaf node and a non-leaf is therefore the
     absence of sub-nodes between a start and an end tag.
   вАҐ optionally non-markup and comments before, after, and between the
     nodes.

   Processing instructions and declarations are typically located at the
beginning of the XML document and at the same level as the root of the
tree.  defined by the document.  Document type declarations are
preserved (so that they can be processed in APL), but are currently
ignored by вОХXML. As a consequence, entity declarations have no effect
and only the predefined XML entities (i.e.  &, <, >, вАЩ, and ") are
recognized (and translated) by вОХXML.

2.40.3 How вОХXML maps XML documents to APL Values
------------------------------------------------

The principal mapping between XML strings and APL values is:

   вАҐ XML document вЖРвЖТ structured (top-level) APL value or variable (= an
     associative array)
   вАҐ XML node вЖРвЖТ structured APL (sub-) value (= an associative (sub-)
     array of either the top-level value or of another XML node)
   вАҐ XML name вЖРвЖТ name of a member in a structured APL value
   вАҐ Other вЖРвЖТ member value

   Every valid name in XML is also a valid name for an APL variable or
structure member.  Unfortunately, mapping XML names directly to APL
member names cannot work because:

   вАҐ In any associative array the names of the members are necessarily
     distinct.  Assigning a value to an already existing member of a
     structured value overwrites the current value of that member
     instead of creating a second member with that value.  On the other
     hand, in XML nodes tags may (and frequently do) occur repeatedly.
     If an XML document contains several nodes with the same tag, then
     the applications usually knows how to interpret the order in which
     the tags occur, but this order may not be detectable at the XML
     level (i.e.  the nodes may not only have the same tag names, but
     also the same attributes and attribute values).

     The applications that use the XML document frequently require that
     the order of XML nodes with the same name remain intact when the
     document is modified.  For example, the entries of a telephone book
     may be sorted alphabetically without XML being aware of that.
     Reading, modifying, and writing back the data in the telephone book
     must therefore not destroy that order.

   вАҐ Likewise, at least for readability reasons, the order of node
     attributes should not be changed.  XML documents are frequently
     processed with text tools like diff which would incorrectly show
     differences between XML documents that are equivalent from an XML
     perspective.

   вАҐ Conflicts between tag names and attribute names.  In XML, the same
     name can designate an attribute in one node and a tag in another
     node.  вОХXML keeps all information from the < of a start tag to the
     > of an end tag in a single associative array, therefore the
     attribute names must somehow differ from the (sub-) tag names.

   вАҐ Every XML node has a tag name that can be used to derive a
     corresponding APL member name.  However, the text segments between
     an XML tag and its corresponding end tag, are a mixture of
     unstructured text, XML subnodes and comments of which only the XML
     subnodes have tags of their own.  These untagged segments may,
     however, contain relevant information and, from an XML standard
     perspective, both their content and their order must be preserved.

   вОХXML solves these issues with a simple naming convention for all
member names in the (recursive) associative array that is produced by
monadic вОХXML. Every member name consists of 3 components that together
yield a valid APL variable name (and therefore a valid member name that
is understood by the APL parser):

   вАҐ A single character вНЩ, вИЖ, or _, that indicates the role of the name
     in the XML document as follows:
        вАҐ the character вНЩ characterizes an attribute name, i.e.  a name
          that was used inside (i.e.  between < and >) of an XML start
          or leaf tag.  The character вНЩ alone is the name of a special
          member which is present in every associative array below the
          top-level and whose value is the original XML tag name of a
          tag, or

        вАҐ the character вИЖ characterizes a name that was synthesized by
          вОХXML itself to tag a text (sub-) segment that has no tag of
          its own.  The corresponding XML entity was not a tag (and
          therefore had no tag name), or

        вАҐ the character _ characterizes the name of an XML entity, i.e.
          a CML name that occurred between the start tag and the
          corresponding end tag (if any: leaf tags have no such
          entities)

   вАҐ a position prefix of the form NN, where NN is the position of the
     member in relation to the tag to which it belongs.  The numbering
     starts at вОХIO and restarts at every XML start or leaf tag.

   вАҐ the attribute name or tag name.  For those parts of an XML entity
     that do not have a tag name, the member name is synthesized by вОХXML
     and the member value will be the text in the XML document with
     predefined XML entities replaced by their single characters, i.e.:
        вАҐ & for &amp,
        вАҐ < for &lt,
        вАҐ > for &gt,
        вАҐ вАЩ for &apos,
        вАҐ " for &quot,
        вАҐ вОХUCS nnn for &#nnn, and
        вАҐ вОХUCS $xxx for &#xxx

   Let NN be a sequence of decimal digits.  Then only the following 4
synthesized names are produced by вОХXML:

   вАҐ вИЖNNcomment for XML comments, i.e.  <!вАФ ...  вАФ> in XML,
   вАҐ вИЖNNdeclaration for XML declarations, i.e.  <?  ...  ?> in XML,
   вАҐ вИЖNNdoctype for document type declarations, i.e.  <!DOCTYPE ...  >
     in XML
   вАҐ вИЖNNtext for unstructured (and hence untagged) text segements in
     XML.

   Every XML name (of a tag or attribute) is also a valid APL name, but
valid APL names may also contain the characters _, вИЖ, and вНЩ which are
not valid in XML and used in the naming convention above to clearly
separate the member names used in APL from the names used in the XML
document.

   The essence of all this is that everything that belongs to an XML
node or document, i.e.  the attributes inside a tag, the sub-nodes
between a start tag and its corresponding end tag (if any),
declarations, etc.  will be contained in a single associative array.

   Examples of APL member names (assuming вОХIOвЖР1):

      вНЩ1              вНЭ the first member in every XML node. Its value is the node tag.
      вИЖ1declaration   вНЭ the first member in most XML documents. E.g. <?xml version= ...>
      вИЖ2text          вНЭ whitespace (LF) between _1вИЖdeclaration and _3вИЖdoctype
      вИЖ3doctype       вНЭ DTD in XML documents that have one. E.g. <!DOCTYPE  ...
      _6Workspace     вНЭ Sub-array for <Workspace ... at position 6.
      вНЩ1wsid          вНЭ first attribute wsid from e.g. <Workspace wsid=...
      вНЩ2year          вНЭ second attribute year

2.40.4 Monadic вОХXML
-------------------

Z вЖР вОХXML B converts APL string B that contains a valid XML document to
an associative APL array Z and vice versa.

   Note: If you convert an associative APL array back to a an XML
document, the result is a possibly very long string containing several
linefeed characters.  That is OK if the string is written to a file, but
causes problems when the string is displayed and longer than вОХPW. The
standard APL folding of output near вОХPW make the string then look
somewhat garbled.  This effect can be suppressed in 2 ways:

  1. set вОХPW large enough, or
  2. prefix the string with вКГ35вОХCR as in the examples below.

2.40.5 Dyadic вОХXML
------------------

Z вЖР A вОХXML B provides a number of convenience functions.  Its left
argument A is an integer function number, possibly followed by arguments
of the function number вЖСA.

   In the following examples, let

      XMLвЖР36 вОХCR """
