2.42 Matrix Product
===================

In standard APL, the inner product Z of two matrices A and B as known
from linear algebra, is:

      ZвЖРA +.√Ч B      вНЭ the most frequent special case of A f.g B

   However, the inner product in APL is more general than the inner
product in linear algebra.  In the general case A f.g B may the
functions f and g also be non-scalar APL primitives or even defined
functions.  This generality may occasionally be helpful, but it comes
with a performance penalty since many argument checks are duplicated.
At the same time A +.√Ч B is by far the most frequent use of the inner
product operator вАЩ.вАЩ.

   For this reason GNU APL also provides a slightly more efficient
dyadic function вИШ (Matrix Product) for the special case +.√Ч of the
dyadic operator вАЩ.вАЩ.  This function вИШ has been optimized for numeric
arguments and computes the matrix product as known from linear algebra.

   For two-dimensional matrices A and B is function вИШ conceptually the
same as +.√Ч:

   AвИШB вЖРвЖТ A +.√Ч B

   However, there are some subtle differences between the function вИШ and
the operator +.√Ч:

   вАҐ A +.√Ч B allows A and B to be of any rank, while AвИШB raises a RANK
     ERROR if the rank of A or B is more than 2.

   вАҐ The product A +.√Ч B can be a vector (e.g.  if A is a vector and B
     is a matrix), usually understood as row-vector.  In contrast (and
     more similar to linear algebra) AвИШB is always a matrix.
   вАҐ In order to preserve the distinction between row vectors and column
     vectors the arguments A and B of вИШ are possibly reshaped according
     to the following rules:

        вАҐ if A and/or B is a scalar then the normal (element-wise)
          product of A and B is computed.  That is, AвИШB вЖРвЖТ A√ЧB.
        вАҐ if A is a APL vector of length N then it is reshaped to a
          row-vector before AвИШB is computed.  In this context, the term
          row-vector shall refer to a matrix of shape (1 N).
        вАҐ if B is a APL vector of length N then it is reshaped to a
          column-vector before AвИШB is computed.  In this context, the
          term column-vector shall refer to a matrix of shape (N 1).

     Examples:

           MвЖР2 2вНі1 2 3 4   вНЭ a matrix
           VвЖР10 11         вНЭ a vector
     
           M +.√Ч V
     32 74
     
           MвИШV
     32
     74
     
           V +.√Ч M
     43 64
     
           VвИШM
     43 64
     
           вНіM +.√Ч V   вНЭ the result is an (APL-) vector of length 2
     2
           вНіV +.√Ч M   вНЭ the result is an (APL-) vector of length 2
     2
           вНіVвИШM       вНЭ the result is row vector
     1 2
           вНіMвИШV       вНЭ the result is column vector
     2 1

   вАҐ A +.√Ч B requires that the number of columns in A is equal to the
     number of rows in B. In contrast, AвИШB has no such requirement and
     will add 0-columns to A resp.  0-rows to B to match the shapes of A
     and B. Naturally, the multiplications of these 0-columns or 0-rows
     is not in fact performed, but optimized away.


